<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos purissima </i>(a rare CNPS list 1B plant) is endemic to northern Santa Barbara Co. This species lacks a lignotuber, has smooth bark, and has clasping leaf bases. Plants produce a gnarled branching pattern. <i>A. rudis </i>(a rare CNPS list 1B plant) is endemic to southern San Luis Obispo and northern Santa Barbara Cos. This species has a lignotuber, shredding bark, and elliptic iso-facial leaves. These species may occur separately as dominants or together as co-dominants in stands, and both species are most abundant in older, mature chaparral at ages > 70 years (Meyer 2004). <br/>
<br/>
Structurally the stands appear to vary between coastal scrub types openly dominated by <i>Artemisia californica, Baccharis pilularis, </i>or <i>Salvia mellifera, </i>a tall chaparral thickly dominated by manzanita, a wooded shrubland sparsely dominated by <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>with an understory of manzanita <i>, </i>or scattered copses of the endemic manzanita species. Fire, other disturbances, and environmental conditions (e.g., slope steepness, depth of sand deposits, and other edaphic features) appear to influence these patterns. Fires recently appeared to encourage seed-sprouting of <i>Arctostaphylos purissima, Ceanothus cuneatus </i>var. <i>fascicularis, </i>and <i>C. impressus</i>. However, recent deaths of young manzanita plants may be related to disease or drought. <br/>
<br/>
The military operations at Vandenberg Air Force Base, recently expanding private housing developments, fragmentation by roads, and mechanical clearing appear as impacts on the Burton Mesa populations. People have raised concern over maintenance of the proper ratio of chaparral, coastal scrub, and woodland dominance in the area (M. Meyer, pers. comm. 2003). Since fire intervals are higher now than in the recent past, issues have been raised as to whether to encourage or discourage fire. The State Lands Commission owns a 405 ha parcel containing this kind of maritime chaparral near Lompoc (Meyer 2004), and the California Department of Fish and Game is developing a longrange management plan for the area. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
